# Public Prosecutor _v_ Mo Weiliang  

### \[2022\] SGDC 133

<table id="info-table"><tbody><tr class="info-row"><td class="txt-label" style="padding: 4px 0px; white-space: nowrap" valign="top">Case Number</td><td class="txt-body">District Arrest Case No 923710 of 2021 &amp; Anor, Magistrate's Appeal No 9107-2022-01</td></tr><tr class="info-row"><td class="txt-label" style="padding: 4px 0px; white-space: nowrap" valign="top">Decision Date</td><td class="txt-body">13 June 2022</td></tr><tr class="info-row"><td class="txt-label" style="padding: 4px 0px; white-space: nowrap" valign="top">Tribunal/Court</td><td class="txt-body">District Court</td></tr><tr class="info-row"><td class="txt-label" style="padding: 4px 0px; white-space: nowrap" valign="top">Coram</td><td class="txt-body">Salina Bte Ishak</td></tr><tr class="info-row"><td class="txt-label" style="padding: 4px 0px; white-space: nowrap" valign="top">Counsel Name(s)</td><td class="txt-body">Jimmy Yap Poh Huat (Traffic Police) for the Prosecution; Tiffanie Lim Jing Wen (Forward Legal LLC) for the accused.</td></tr><tr class="info-row"><td class="txt-label" style="padding: 4px 0px; white-space: nowrap" valign="top">Parties</td><td class="txt-body">Public Prosecutor — Mo Weiliang</td></tr></tbody></table>

Criminal Procedure and Sentencing – Statutory Offences – Road Traffic Act – Drink driving – Irresponsible driving

\[LawNet Editorial Note: An appeal to this decision has been filed in MA 9107/2022/01.\]

13 June 2022

### District Judge Salina Bte Ishak:

## Background

1       The accused, Mr Mo Weiliang, a 38 years-old male Singapore citizen faced two charges namely:

> (a)     **DAC 923710-2021**

**1st Charge**

> are charged that you, on 13 July 2021, at about 7.03 p.m., along Upper Aljunied Road ESSO petrol kiosk, Singapore, whilst driving motorcar SKS2149L, did have so much alcohol in your body that the proportion of it in your breath, to wit, not less than 100 microgrammes of alcohol in 100 millilitres of breath, exceeded the prescribed limit of 35 microgrammes of alcohol in 100 millilitres of breath, and you have thereby committed an offence under Section 67(1)(b) and punishable under Section 67(1) read with Section 67(2)(a) of the Road Traffic Act (Cap 276, 2004 Rev Ed).

> (b)     **DAC 923711-2021**

**2** nd **Charge**

> are charged that you, on 13 July 2021, at about 7.03 p.m., along Upper Aljunied Road ESSO petrol kiosk, Singapore, did drive motorcar SKS2149L, without due care and attention, to wit, by failing to keep a proper lookout and grazed the victim namely Tan Mui Kee, and hurt was caused to the victim and you have thereby committed an offence under Section 65(1)(a) punishable under Section 65(4)(c) read with Section 65(4)(a) and Section 65(6)(g) of the Road Traffic Act (Cap 276, 2004 Rev Ed) (“RTA”).

2       On 31 May 2022, the accused pleaded guilty to both charges and admitted to the Statement of Facts without any qualification.

3       After carefully considering the Defence’s written plea in mitigation and the Prosecution’s submissions on sentence, I sentenced the accused as follows:

> (a)      **DAC 923710-2021** – eight weeks’ imprisonment and disqualified him from holding or obtaining all classes of driving licences for a period of five years with effect from date of release and

> (b)      **DAC 923711-2021** – three weeks’ imprisonment and disqualified him from holding or obtaining all classes of driving licences for a period of four years with effect from date of release.

As I ordered the sentences for both charges to run concurrently, his aggregate sentence was eight weeks’ imprisonment and disqualification from holding or obtaining all classes of driving licences for a period of five years with effect from date of release.

4       The accused being dissatisfied with my decision had filed his Notice of Appeal against his sentence on 1 June 2022. On 3 June 2022, bail pending appeal was offered to the accused. It was fixed at $20,000 with one surety. To date, he is presently serving his sentence and his earliest date of release is on 8 July 2022.

5       Having set out the background for the present case, I now provide the reasons for my decision.

## Salient Facts

6       The complainant is Sergeant Jeremiah Phua En Rong attached to Traffic Police. The accused was the driver of motorcar SKS2149L at the time of the accident. The victim is Tan Mui Kee, male, 58 years old. She was a customer of the Esso petrol kiosk along Upper Aljunied Road, Singapore at the material time.

7       On 13 July 2021 at about 2:00 plus pm, the accused was at an event hall located at 213 Lavender Street for his wedding. The accused had consumed one bottle of beer, which he started drinking at about 2.30pm. The accused stopped drinking at about 4.30pm and left the location at about 6:00pm.

8       On the same day, at about 7.03pm, the accused drove his motorcar SKS2149L to the Esso petrol kiosk along Upper Aljunied Road, Singapore. While at the petrol kiosk, he drove without due care and attention, by failing to keep a proper lookout and grazed against the victim who was standing next to her motorcar while refuelling and hurt was caused to the victim by such driving. The footage from the Esso petrol kiosk CCTV revealed that the victim was standing on the right side of her motorcar when the accused came towards the right side of the victim and the distance was so close that the accused’s motorcar grazed against the victim squeezing her between the two cars. The accused continued to drive forward causing the victim to fall to the ground at the rear of her car and at the same time the accused’s motorcar ran over the victim’s foot.

![](data:image;base64,)

9       The complainant attended to the accident and approached the accused. Upon talking to the accused, the complainant noticed that the accused reeked of alcohol. The accused admitted to drinking alcoholic drinks before driving the vehicle. A breathalyzer test was conducted on the accused and the test result shows “Fail”. The accused was arrested and escorted to Traffic Police for Breath Analyzing Device (BAD) test.

10     The BAD test was conducted by Senior Staff Sergeant Nur Diana on the 13 July 2021 at about 8.49pm at Traffic Police. The breath test revealed that the proportion of alcohol in accused’s breath was 100ug of alcohol in every 100 millilitres of breath. The prescribed limit is 35ug of alcohol per 100 millilitres of breath.

11     As a result of the accident, the victim sustained tenderness over her right first three toes and complained of pain to her right toes and back body. She was conveyed from the scene by ambulance to Raffles Hospital. The victim was treated as an outpatient with three days medical leave. There was no damage to the accused’s motorcar. The accused made restitution to the victim, compensating her for to an amount between $1,400 to $1,500. Both the victim and the accused were unable to recall the exact amount of restitution.

12     Pursuant to Section 64(8) of the Road Traffic Act, the accused is considered a serious offender when he is convicted of an offence under Section 67(1)(b) of the Road Traffic Act, Chapter 276 in relation to the accused’s driving.

## Sentencing

### Prescribed Penalties

#### s 67(1)(b) RTA

13     The prescribed penalty for an offence of drink driving under s 67(1)(_b_) of the RTA is a fine of not less than $2,000 and not more than $10,000 or to imprisonment for a term not exceeding 12 months or to both and, in the case of a second or subsequent conviction, to a fine of not less than $5,000 and not more than $20,000 and to imprisonment for a term not exceeding two years.

14     In addition, pursuant to s 67(2)(_a_) of the RTA unless the court for special reasons thinks fit to not order or to order otherwise, the court must order that the person be disqualified from holding or obtaining a driving licence for at least two years for a first offender.

#### s 65(1)(a) RTA

15     The prescribed penalty for an offence of driving without due care and attention under s 65(1)(_a_) of the RTA punishable under s 65(5)(_a_) is a fine not exceeding $1,500 or to imprisonment for a term not exceeding 6 months or to both. Further, pursuant to s 64(8) of the RTA, as the accused has also been convicted for an offence under s 67 of the RTA, the accused is liable as a serious offender to a fine of not less than $2,000 and not more than $10,000 or to imprisonment for a term not exceeding 12 months or to both, _in addition_ to any punishment under s 65(1)(_a_) of the RTA.

16     In addition, s 65(6)(_i_) of the RTA provides that unless the court for special reasons thinks fit to not order or to order otherwise, the court must order that the person be disqualified from holding or obtaining a driving licence for at least two years for a first offender.

## Antecedents

17     The accused had no similar antecedents.

## Prosecution’s Submissions on Sentence

18     It was the Prosecution’s position that the accused’s BAD reading fell under Band 4 of the sentencing framework in _Rafael Voltaire Alzate v Public Prosecutor_ <span class="citation">\[2022\] 3 SLR 993</span> (“_Rafael_”). As it was almost three times the prescribed limit, his culpability should be pegged as high. There was slight harm as the injuries were minor. It was submitted that as the accused had drinks and had driven, this made him liable as a serious offender.

19     It was further submitted that based on the sentencing framework in _Stansilas Fabian Kester v Public Prosecutor_ <span class="citation">\[2017\] 5 SLR 755</span> ("_Stansilas_") at \[78\], where the culpability is high and the harm slight, the sentencing range should be one to two months imprisonment. It was the Prosecution’s case that as the framework was set up prior to the amendment to the RTA, the sentencing range for the present offence should be doubled to two to four months imprisonment. Accordingly, the Prosecution sought a sentence of ten to 12 weeks’ imprisonment and five years’ disqualification for the drink driving charge.

20     In respect of the charge of driving without due care and attention, it was submitted that the culpability was on the moderate category as the accused had driven shortly after he had drinks. The harm was pegged as low as the victim sustained minor injuries. The Prosecution sought a sentence of three weeks’ imprisonment and three years’ disqualification. It was further submitted that the sentences were to run concurrently.

## Mitigation

21     In the written plea in mitigation, Defence Counsel Ms Tiffanie Ling Jin Wen had set out her client’s personal background as well as the circumstances that led to the commission of the offences.

22     According to the Defence, at around 6:40pm whilst on the way home, the accused made a detour to the ESSO petrol station along Upper Aljunied Road for petrol. While turning into the petrol station, he noticed the kiosks on the left were fully occupied, and therefore, drove to the utmost left lane to wait for his turn at the kiosk.

23     It was the Defence’s position that as the accused was turning his vehicle, the victim appeared on the left side of her vehicle which was stationary along the kiosk. The accused turned his vehicle a little to the left to avoid contact with her. However, as he was doing so, he heard a woman’s voice. The accused proceeded to stop his vehicle immediately. His wife then got out of the car to check what was going on. The victim was then already on the ground and the accused’s wife attended to her immediately by massaging her toes and ensuring her wellbeing until the paramedics arrived.

24     The Defence had also set out the following mitigating factors at \[13\] to \[16\] of the written plea in mitigation namely:

> (a)     The accused had promptly contacted the victim after the incident on the same night itself to apologise for his irresponsible act and to make prompt restitution of her medical bills. This illustrated his sincere remorse for his transgression.

> (b)     He had no similar antecedents and this was his first brush under the RTA. The accused had been driving for 17 years and has ordinarily been a meticulous and careful driver but for this incident.

> (c)     He was deeply regretful for his actions and is also committed to ensure that such an incident will not happen again. In the present case, he had a regrettable lapse in judgment but he makes no excuses for his wrongdoings and he prays for leniency.

> (d)     He had co-operated with the Police to the best of his ability. He was forthcoming in his dealings with the Investigating Officer and this should have assisted the investigations in no small measure.

#### s 67(1)(b) RTA

25     It was submitted that in _Rafael_, the High Court had set out the sentencing framework for offences under s 67(1)(_b_) of the RTA. It was highlighted that the High Court had held that the framework is only applicable where no harm to person or property has been caused and that the framework provides only neutral starting points.

26     It was further submitted that the High Court in _Stansilas_ held that in considering the circumstances and gravity of a drink driving offence, the factors to be taken into consideration are the degree of harm caused and the culpability of the offender. The offender’s alcohol level as well as the manner of driving would be taken into consideration in determining the culpability of the offender.

27     It was the Defence’s position that applying the sentencing guidelines in _Stansilas_, the harm caused was slight as the injuries the victim suffered was minor. According to the medical report dated 3 May 2022, the victim suffered pain to her first three toes and her left buttock and was treated outpatient with three days medical leave.

28     In relation to the accused’s culpability, it was submitted that it fell within the medium range as his level placed him on the highest band of the _Rafael_ sentencing framework. Accordingly, with slight harm and medium culpability, it was the Defence’s position that the present case fell under the category where the indicative sentencing range entails a term of imprisonment of up to a month.

29     In calibrating the sentence, the Defence referred to the case of _Public Prosecutor v Shin Seung Ho_ <span class="citation">\[2022\] SGDC 33</span> (“_Shin_”). The accused was a first-time offender who had not less than 109ug of alcohol in 100 millilitres of breath which placed him on the highest band of the sentencing framework in _Rafael_. There were several aggravating factors as he had driven against the flow of traffic, been involved in two separate accidents where he collided into two vehicles at different parts of the carpark and incurred slight property damage. A sentence of one week’s imprisonment and 48 months of disqualification for all classes of vehicle was imposed.

30     Applying _Shin_ to the present case, it was submitted that the accused was similarly a first-time offender who had not less than 100ug of alcohol in 100 millilitres of breath which placed him on the highest band of the sentencing framework in _Rafael_. He had driven without incident until he had reached the petrol kiosk and it was submitted that his manner of driving is therefore indicative that he had control of his faculties at that point in time.

31     However, the Defence conceded that even though the accused had driven slowly at the petrol kiosk, hurt was caused to the victim due to his lapse in judgement as he had failed to accurately gauge the distance between his car and the victim whilst making a turn. It was submitted that a sentence of one week’s imprisonment and four years disqualification was just and appropriate in the circumstances for the first charge.

#### s 65(1)(a) RTA

32     In respect of the second charge, it was highlighted that the Court in _Shin_ held that the sentencing framework set out by the High Court in _Wu Zhi Yong v Public Prosecutor_ <span class="citation">\[2021\] SGHC 261</span> (“_Wu Zhi Yong_”) for offences punishable under s 64(2C)(_a_) read with ss 64(2C)(_c_) of the RTA provides useful guidance as to how offences under s 65(1) of the RTA should be dealt with.

33     It was submitted that the _Wu Zhi Yong_ sentencing framework consists of two steps, the first being to identify the band applicable to the offences at hand and the indicative starting point with reference to that band, having regard to the offence-specific factors present. The second being to calibrate the sentence from that starting point by having regard to the offender-specific factors present.

34     Applying the first step of the _Wu Zhi Yong_ sentencing framework to the present case, it was submitted that the accused’s offences fell within the lower end of Band 2. It was further submitted that the only offence-specific aggravating present was his high alcohol level. While the Defence conceded that the accused should not have driven after consuming alcohol, it was the Defence’s position that the harm caused was due to his failure to accurately gauge the distance between his car and the victim whilst making a turn rather than the inability to control his vehicle.

35     With regards to the accused’s culpability, the Defence referred to the cases of _Shin_ and _Ashwin_. While both cases involved only property damage, it was submitted that sentencing guidance can be taken from the manner and mode of offences in both cases. The manner of driving of the accused in _Shin_ was indicative of an impairment of his ability to drive and his poor control of the vehicle as he had driven the flow of traffic twice and collided into two vehicles in a carpark. In _Ashwin_, the accused drove into a bus-stop, mounted the kerb and collided into two safety bollards with such force that one of the bollards was uprooted, swerved right and mounted the kerb of the central divider.

36     In the present case, it was submitted that the accused’s manner of driving prior to the incident and even up to the incident itself did not reflect the impairment of the ability to drive and poor control of his vehicle when compared to _Shin_ and _Ashwin_. It was the Defence’s position that the accused’s manner of driving was indicative that he had full control of his faculties. Hence, taking the above into consideration, it was submitted that the indicative starting point was one month’s imprisonment and three years disqualification for all classes.

37     In calibrating the sentence having regard to the offender-specific factors, it was submitted that the accused was a first-time offender who had pleaded guilty to both his charges. He had made restitution and he was sincerely remorseful for his actions. Accordingly, taking the above and the sentencing precedents provided into consideration, it was further submitted the imprisonment term should be calibrated downwards to a term of two weeks.

#### Global Sentence

38     It was submitted that the High Court in _Wu Zhi Yong_ held that when the “serious offender” offender provision applies, the general rule is that sentences should run concurrently insofar as any term of imprisonment or disqualification order is concerned. This is because the “serious offender” provision would only apply when the facts underlying both offences are the same.

39     Given that the facts underlying the first charge was in relation to the same act of driving which gave rise to the second charge, the offences engage an identical set of facts. It was further submitted that the sentences for the first charge and second charge should run concurrently as the punishment for the second charge would already have been enhanced on account of the serious offender provision pursuant to s 65(4)(_c_) of the RTA. Accordingly, the Defence urged that a global sentence of two weeks’ imprisonment and four years disqualification for all classes be imposed.

## Prosecution’s Reply

40     In response to the Defence’s position on sentence, it was highlighted that in _Shin_ and _Ashwin_, no hurt was caused but as the present case involves injuries, the sentences imposed should be higher.

## My decision on sentence

#### Sentencing framework for drink driving

41     In determining the appropriate sentence to be imposed in respect of the drink driving charge as the accused was a first offender, I had considered the sentencing framework established by Menon CJ in _Rafael_ as a neutral starting point.

In the present case as the accused’s alcohol level was 100ug, it fell within Band 4 of the framework.

42     In the application of the above sentencing framework, Menon CJ made two additional points at \[32\] and \[33\]:

> (a)     The sentencing framework is only applicable where no harm to person or property has eventuated; and

> (b)     The framework provides only neutral starting points based on the relative seriousness of the offence and considering only the level of alcohol in the offender’s body. Regard should still be had to any aggravating or mitigating circumstances (see _Edwin Suse Nathen v Public Prosecutor_ <span class="citation">\[2013\] 4 SLR 1139</span> (“_Edwin Suse_”) at \[22\]) and if the former, if they exist, could result in the custodial threshold being crossed.

43     Accordingly, I was mindful that this framework is applicable where no harm to person or property has eventuated. This framework only provides starting points based on the relative seriousness of the offence and considering only the level of alcohol in the offender’s body. When sentencing, I would still have to consider whether there was any aggravating or mitigating circumstances and to make the necessary calibrations to the relevant starting points. In determining the appropriate sentence, I would also consider other relevant factors such as the manner of driving, the type of vehicle, the distance travelled, the road and traffic conditions, any impairment of the ability to drive or whether there was accident resulting in harm to person or property.

44     In the present case, both the Prosecution and the Defence agreed that the custodial threshold had been crossed when and because the accused’s drunk driving had resulted in injury to the victim. It was undisputed that the harm caused to the victim was slight was she suffered minor injuries. The issue for my determination was the appropriate length of the custodial sentence as well as the period of disqualification for all classes of vehicles from release.

45     At \[37\] to \[38\] of _Stansilas_ Menon CJ held:

> 37…A driver’s alcohol level served as an indicator of his unfitness to drive due to his alcohol intake. This provides a reason for imposing heavier punishment on drivers with higher alcohol levels. There was an increased need for protection of the public from drivers with higher alcohol levels, given the enhanced threat to public safety they posed. There is an increased need for protection of the public from such drivers, given the enhanced threat to public safety posed by the correspondingly more severe impairment of their ability and fitness to drive

> 38    By enacting an outright prohibition against driving with an excessive alcohol level, Parliament makes its stance against drunk driving clear – it is to stamp out the scourge of drunk driving which is a serious menace to the safety of the community. Put shortly, these stricter laws against drunk driving seek to ensure the _physical safety of road users_…

46     Menon CJ further held at \[74\] of _Stansilas_:

> 74 To begin, it seems to me that in assessing the overall gravity of the offence, it is (as noted above) relevant to consider, first, the degree of harm caused; and second, the culpability of the offender. In relation to the latter consideration, this will entail consideration of the extent to which the offender’s alcohol level exceeds the prescribed limit as well as the manner of the offender’s driving.

47     At \[75\] of his judgment, he had observed that it was possible to calibrate harm as being slight, moderate, serious and very serious; and culpability as being low, medium or high. These were indicative categories to assist analysis and to be assessed as a matter of common sense.

#### Level of alcohol

48     In the present case, I considered the fact that the accused was a first offender who had pleaded guilty to the present charge. He had started drinking at about 2.30pm, stopped drinking at about 4.30pm and left the event hall at Lavender Street at about 6:00pm. His alcohol level was 100ug of alcohol in 100 millilitres of breath which was almost thrice the legal limit and was within Band 4 of the _Rafael_ sentencing framework. He had also driven for some distance between the event hall at Lavender Street to the Esso petrol station at Upper Aljunied. For an offence of drink driving where no harm to person or property has eventuated, the range of sentence for Band 4 would be a fine between $8,000 to $10,000 and disqualification of between 48 to 60 months for all classes of vehicles.

49     As observed by Menon CJ in _Stansilas_:

> _The offender’s alcohol level_

> 52 The same principle as that identified in _Edwin Suse_ (\[2\] supra) at \[22\] applies – “in general, the higher the alcohol level, the greater should be \[the punishment\]”. There are two reasons why this is correct as a matter of principle. The first reason concerns the potential consequences of a high alcohol level which in turn affects the risks imposed on other road users. The higher the offender’s alcohol level, the more likely it is that his driving ability has been impaired and the greater the extent of the likely impairment.

> 53 The second reason concerns the culpability of the offender. The higher the offender’s alcohol level, the higher the extent of his disregard for the law and for the well-being of others. It indicates the offender’s level of personal responsibility and, consequently, his “relative blameworthiness” and culpability. This is relevant even in a case where there is no indication of actual impairment of one’s driving ability (for instance, where the offender does not display any lack of control over his vehicle).

#### Consequences of the act

50     In the present case, the accused had driven his motorcar without due care and attention within the Esso petrol kiosk located along Upper Aljunied Road and had grazed against the victim who was standing next to her motorcar while refuelling. Footage from the Esso petrol kiosk CCTV showed that the victim was standing on the right side of her motorcar when the accused came towards the right side of the victim.

51     It was clear from the footage at \[8\] above that there was insufficient space between the victim’s vehicle and the guard railing of the petrol kiosk for the accused’s motorcar to pass through safely. Despite this, presumably because his judgment was impaired due to his very high level of alcohol, the accused continued to drive forward, squeezing the hapless victim between the two cars and caused the victim to fall to the ground onto her back at the rear of her car and at the same time the accused’s motorcar ran over the victim’s foot. The accused did not stop his vehicle but continued to drive forward past the petrol kiosk until he was alerted by the other persons in the vicinity of the petrol station to stop. The accused then remained his motorcar despite being approached by what appeared to a uniformed Esso pump attendant. It was evident that the accused clearly had little or no regard for the well-being of the victim despite being aware of her presence at the location prior to the accident.

52     This is contrary to the Defence’s position that after the accused heard a woman’s voice, he had stopped his vehicle immediately. The assertion that his wife then got out of the car immediately to check what was going on was not evident from the footage. Instead, the footage showed other members of the public attending to the victim after the accident as she remained seated on the ground.

53     Based on the evidence before me, I disagreed with the Defence’s position that the harm caused was due to his failure to accurately gauge the distance between his car and the victim whilst making a turn rather than the inability to control his vehicle. I also rejected the Defence’s assertion that the accused’s manner of driving was indicative that he had full control of his motorcar. The accused had driven forward to squeeze past the victim and her car although it was clearly unsafe for him to do so and had proceeded to drive forward instead of stopping his vehicle immediately. It was only fortuitous that the victim had not sustained any serious injuries when the accused’s motorcar grazed against her, causing her to fall and land on her back as well as running over her foot. Furthermore, the accused had been drinking over a period of two hours at his wedding and had elected to drive his vehicle with his wife as his passenger less than two hours after having consumed alcohol. Accordingly, I agreed with the Prosecution and found that his level of culpability was high.

54     Apart from the actual harm caused, I was of the view there was also potential physical harm posed other persons present within the vicinity of the Esso petrol station. In the present case, the offences were committed on a Tuesday evening on 13 July 2021 at 7:03pm when one would expect the presence of other road users at the Esso petrol station and were in fact seen in the footage. As the accused’s judgment was impaired due to his very high level of alcohol, by driving while under influence of alcohol he had also posed a serious risk to other road users. As stated above, the higher the offender’s alcohol level, the more likely it is that his driving ability has been impaired and the greater the extent of the likely impairment.

55     In the present case, as the harm was slight and the accused’s culpability was high, I agreed with the Prosecution the sentencing range for the present offence was two to four months imprisonment. The _Stansilas_ sentencing range at \[78\] of up to two months’ imprisonment for slight harm and high culpability was premised on the pre-RTA amendment punishment of a minimum fine of $1,000 and maximum fine of $5,000 or to imprisonment not exceeding six months for a first offender. In the present case, the accused was liable to a prescribed punishment which has since been doubled, namely a minimum fine of $2,000 and maximum fine of $10,000 or to imprisonment not exceeding 12 months. Hence, an upward calibration of the sentencing range was necessary to give full effect to the RTA amendment where the aim was to reflect Parliament’s intention to further deter the scourge of drink driving and for the court to consider the full range of the statutory penalties.

56     In my view, the appropriate starting range for the present charge is ten to 12 weeks’ imprisonment. This was the sentence sought by the Prosecution. Nevertheless, after giving the necessary weight to fact that the accused was a first offender who had pleaded guilty, his cooperation with the authorities and the remorse shown by making full restitution for the injury caused, I was of the view a downward calibration to eight weeks’ imprisonment was just and appropriate. Such a sentence would fulfil the objectives of punishment, the protection of the public as well as deterrence. In my view the proposed sentence by the Defence of one week’s imprisonment was inadequate in view of the accused’s very high level of alcohol and the fact that personal injury was occasioned. I agreed with the Prosecution that _Shin_’s case can be distinguished from the present case as there was no harm caused and the restitution for the property damage was $40.

57     As for the appropriate length of the disqualification order, I was guided by both the sentencing framework in _Rafael_ as well as the recent case of _Kwan Weiguang v Public Prosecutor_ <span class="citation">\[2022\] SGHC 121</span> (“_Kwan_”). Based on the _Rafael_ framework, the range of disqualification period for Band 4 was 48 to 60 months where no harm to person or property has eventuated. In _Kwan_ at \[65\] to \[71\], the High Court held that the relevant and material factors when determining the period of disqualification are:

> (a)     Circumstances of the commission of the offence;

> (b)     Continued ability to drive and attitude towards other road users;

58     In the present case, the accused’s judgment was impaired due to his very high level of alcohol, personal injury was caused to the victim by his poor control of his vehicle and had also posed a serious risk to the physical safety of other road users when drove while under influence of alcohol. At the material time, from the footage it was evident that there were other road users present within the vicinity of the petrol station. Despite having drinks for over two hours, while under the influence of alcohol, he had also driven for some distance with his wife from Lavender Street to the Esso petrol station at Upper Aljunied. The accused had shown a blatant disregard for the physical safety of other road users including his wife and a lack of personal responsibility. Based on the above circumstances, it was within the public’s interest to remove such a driver from the roads for a substantial period of time. In my view, taking all the above circumstances into account, in my view a disqualification period of five years for all classes of vehicles from release was appropriate to fulfil the objectives of punishment, the protection of the public and deterrence.

59     I now turn to the second charge under s 65(1)(_a_) of the RTA.

#### Sentencing framework for irresponsible driving

60     The primary offence of driving without due care or reasonable consideration for other persons using the road is encapsulated under s 65(1) of the RTA. The subsequent subsections from ss 65(2) to 65(4) are the penalty prescribing provisions, each tiered according to the degree of hurt caused and for s 65(5), for any other case of non-personal injury or potential harm.

61     The present offence under s 65(1)(_a_) of the RTA was enacted on 1 November 2019, following the passing of the Road Traffic (Amendment) Act 2019 (Act 19 of 2019). The Amendment Act arose out of a review of the RTA and it aimed to provide stronger deterrence against irresponsible driving.

62     Presently there is no existing sentencing framework enunciated by the High Court for offences under s 65(1), particularly for an offence punishable under s 65(5)(_a_) read s 65(5)(_c_) with of the RTA. Although the present case concerns the second category of irresponsible driving, due to the similarity in the structure of the statutory provisions for both forms of irresponsible driving under s 64(1) and s 65(1), I was of the view the observations as well as the sentencing approach set out by Menon CJ in _Wu Zhi Yong_ provides some useful guidance on how an offence under s 65(1) should be dealt with.

63     In my view the offence-specific factors set out by Menon CJ in _Wu Zhi Yong_ at \[36\], which dealt with offences under s 64 of the RTA where there was no hurt caused could apply equally to offences under s 65(1) of the RTA. In _Wu Zhi Yong_, after a careful consideration of the different sentencing approaches at \[22\] to \[29\] Menon CJ had prescribed the sentencing band approach when dealing with offences punishable under s 64(2C)(_a_) read with ss 64(2C)(_c_) of the RTA. At \[30\] and \[48\] of the judgment, Menon CJ had set out the following sentencing approach:

> _The sentencing approach_

> 30 At the first step, as set out in _Terence Ng_ at \[39\], the court should identify the band applicable to the offence and the indicative starting point with reference to that band, having regard to the _offence_\-specific factors present. These would encompass factors relating to the manner and mode by which the offence was committed, as well as the harm caused by the offender. At the second step, the court would have regard to the _offender_\-specific factors, being the aggravating and mitigating factors that are personal to the offender...

> 48 At the second step of the analysis, the court will have regard to the offender-specific factors. Examples of these factors have been set out at \[62\] – \[71\] of _Terence Ng_ and apply equally in the present framework. Offender-specific aggravating factors include offences taken into consideration for the purposes of sentencing, the presence of relevant antecedents (apart from where the offender’s antecedents have been taken into account under the “repeat offender” or “serious repeat offender” provisions), and evidence showing a lack of remorse. Offender-specific mitigating factors include evidence of genuine remorse and an offender’s youth.

#### Offence-specific factors

64     Hence, in my view, the sentencing band approach would be the appropriate sentencing approach when dealing with the second category of irresponsible driving with the necessary calibration made to the range of sentences in each band. Accordingly guided by the sentencing approach as set out in _Wu Zhi Yong_, I first considered the offence-specific factors to determine the appropriate sentencing band where the present offence should be situated. In my view, the offence-specific factors considered by the High Court in _Wu Zhi Yong_ at \[36\] as set out below under the sentencing bands would also be relevant in the present case, namely:

> (_a_)     _Serious potential harm_: Apart from actual harm, it has long been accepted that regard should also be had to the potential harm that can result from the act of dangerous or reckless driving:(see _Stansilas_ at \[47\]; _Public Prosecutor v Koh Thiam Huat_ <span class="citation">\[2017\] 4 SLR 1099</span> (“Koh Thiam Huat” at \[41\]). The level of potential harm would be “assessed against facts which would include … the condition of the road, the volume of traffic or number of pedestrians actually on or which might reasonably be expected to be on the road at the relevant time, the speed and manner of driving, visibility at the relevant time, the type of vehicle, and any particular vulnerabilities (_eg_ a truck or car colliding into a motorcycle or pedestrian: _Neo Chuan Sheng v Public Prosecutor_ <span class="citation">\[2020\] SGHC 97</span> at \[22\]. As is evident, these relate to the circumstances of driving that could increase the danger posed to road users (see Edwin Suse at \[28\]). Where an assessment of these facts reveal that the potential harm occasioned to road users would have been serious, this would be an aggravating factor;

> (_b_)     _Serious property damage_: The extent of property damage caused is a relevant sentencing factor. As a general rule, the amount of any loss or damage may serve as a proxy indicator of harm;

> (_c_)     _High alcohol level found in the accused person’s blood or breath_: A high level of alcohol that substantially exceeds the prescribed limit would be an aggravating factor. As noted by the court in _Stansilas_ at \[37\], an offender’s alcohol level is an indicator of his inability or unfitness to drive due to his alcohol intake, and heavier punishment should therefore be imposed on drivers with higher alcohol levels. This determination of whether an offender’s alcohol level is high can be made with reference to the sentencing framework for an offence under s 67, set out in _Rafael Voltaire_ at \[31\], which is calibrated in accordance with the alcohol levels found in an offender’s blood or breath. In the context of sentencing under s 64(2C)(c), this will be a factor of particular importance;

> (_d_)     _An offender’s reason or motivation for driving_: The court in _Edwin s/o Suse_ held that an offender’s reason or motivation for driving could be an aggravating (or conceivably, in some circumstances, even a mitigating) factor in respect of an offence of drink driving. The court further considered that the gravity of an offender’s conduct would be increased if he had, at that time, been driving a passenger for hire or reward (at \[33\]);

> (_e_)     _Increased culpability_: In _Koh Thiam Huat_ at \[41\], the court considered that factors _increasing_ an accused person’s culpability for an offence of dangerous driving would include a _particularly dangerous manner_ of driving. Examples of such aggravating factors include excessive speeding or deliberate dangerous driving, such as in “hell riding” cases (see _Koh Thiam Huat_ at \[41\]).;

> (_f_)     _The offender’s conduct following the offence or attempt to evade arrest_: Conduct that is “belligerent or violent” upon arrest would constitute an aggravating factor: _Edwin Suse_ at \[32\]. Likewise, the failure to stop in an attempt to evade arrest or to avoid apprehension should also weigh against an offender: _Public Prosecutor v Lee Meng Soon_ <span class="citation">\[2007\] 4 SLR(R) 240</span> at \[33\].

65     Apart from the factors listed above, another relevant factor to be considered would be the number of victims involved. Where there are multiple victims impacted by the accused’s irresponsible driving under the influence of alcohol, this would be regarded as an aggravating factor.

66     As the accused is regarded as a serious offender, he is liable to the prescribed punishment under s 65(5)(_c_) of the RTA which is _in addition_ to any punishment under s 65(5)(_a_) of the RTA. This is in view of Parliament’s intention to punish offenders for the aggravated conduct of driving without due care and attention or without reasonable consideration for others using the road while under the influence of alcohol. Hence, a court can impose a fine of more than $2,000 and not exceeding $11,500 or to imprisonment for a term not exceeding 18 months or to both.

67     In _Shin_’s case which involved similar charges as the present case, at \[63\] to \[65\] I had calibrated the sentencing framework in _Wu Zhi Yong_ for serious offenders under s 65(5)(_c_) read with s 65(5)(_a_) of the RTA. The recalibrated sentencing band is set out below:

#### Band 1

68     In my view, Band 1 would involve an offence with a lower level of seriousness, where the offender’s blood alcohol level is also likely to be at the lowest or second lowest bands in the framework set out in _Rafael_ with no offence-specific aggravating factors. A range of a fine between $2,500 to $11,500 and/or up to one month’s imprisonment and a disqualification period of two years to three years for all classes of vehicles can be considered.

#### Band 2

69     Band 2 would involve a higher level of seriousness and would usually contain two or more offence-specific aggravating factors. The level of culpability and the blood alcohol level will typically both be on the highest band or second highest band of the framework in _Rafael_. In my view, a range of between one month’s imprisonment and up to nine months’ imprisonment and disqualification for a period between three to four years can be considered. The accused’s level of culpability would typically be in the medium range.

#### Band 3

70     The final band would be reserved for the most serious cases of driving without due care and attention or without reasonable consideration for others using the road while under the influence of alcohol where there are multiple aggravating factors including alcohol levels being at the highest band of the framework in _Rafael Voltaire_ and where the offender’s level of culpability is high. For such cases, a range of between nine months and up to eighteen months’ imprisonment and disqualification for a period of four to five years would be appropriate.

#### Calibration of sentence

71     The next step would be for the court to calibrate the sentence after having regard to the offender-specific factors. The relevant factors would include offences that are taken into consideration for the purposes of sentencing, the presence of relevant antecedents and evidence showing a lack of remorse. Offender-specific mitigating factors include a clean record, an early plea of guilt, evidence of genuine remorse and an offender’s youth.

72     I now turn to the facts of the present case.

#### Offence-specific factors

## Manner and mode of offence

73     As set out at earlier, the accused while under the influence of alcohol at the highest band of the sentencing framework in _Rafael_ had driven his motorcar without due care and attention within the Esso petrol kiosk located along Upper Aljunied Road and had grazed against the victim who was standing next to her motorcar while refuelling. From the footage, it was evident that there was insufficient space between the victim’s vehicle and the guard railing of the petrol kiosk for the accused’s motorcar to pass through safely.

74     Despite this, presumably because his judgment was impaired due to his very high level of alcohol, the accused continued to drive forward, squeezing the hapless victim between the two cars and caused the victim to fall to the ground onto her back at the rear of her car and at the same time the accused’s motorcar ran over the victim’s foot. The accused did not stop his vehicle but continued to drive forward past the petrol kiosk until he was alerted by the other persons in the vicinity of the petrol station to stop. The victim suffered tenderness over her right first three toes and complained of pain to her right toes and back body. She was conveyed to Raffles Hospital where she was treated as an outpatient with three days medical leave.

75     Apart from the actual harm caused, as stated earlier, there was also potential harm to posed other persons present within the vicinity of the petrol station. In the present case, the offences were committed on a Tuesday evening on 13 July 2021 at 7:03pm when one would expect the presence of other motorists at the Esso petrol station and were in fact seen in the footage.

76     In the present case, the offence-specific aggravating factors were the very high level of alcohol, the high degree of carelessness in his driving, the actual harm occasioned to the victim as well as the potential harm to other road users within the vicinity of the petrol station. Under such circumstances, I was of the view that his level of culpability was medium and the level of harm slight.

77     Based on the above, as there were several offence-specific aggravating factors present, I was of the view that the present case fell within Band 2 where the range was between one month’s imprisonment and up to nine months’ imprisonment and disqualification for a period between three to four years. It was undisputed that the custodial threshold had been crossed in the present case and the starting point for the present case should be at the lowest end of Band 2 _ie_ one month’s imprisonment.

#### Offender-specific factors

78     The next step was for me to calibrate the sentence after considering offender-specific factors. The accused had pleaded guilty to both charges, he was a first offender who had co-operated with the authorities and he had made restitution to the victim. He was remorseful for his actions.

79     After considering both the aggravating factors as well as the mitigating factors, I had calibrated the sentence downwards to three weeks’ imprisonment. I agreed with the Prosecution that the sentence of three weeks’ imprisonment was appropriate based on the circumstances of the present case. In my view the proposed sentence of two weeks’ imprisonment by the Defence was inadequate in the several offence-specific aggravating factors present in this case.

80     As for the appropriate length of the disqualification order, I was guided by both the sentencing framework in _Wu Zhi Yong_ as well as the recent case of _Kwan_ as cited above_._ Based on the _Wu Zhi Yong_ framework, the range of disqualification period for Band 2 was three to four years. It was clear that it was within the public’s interest to remove such a driver from the roads for a substantial period of time.

81     In my view, taking all the above circumstances into account, a disqualification period of four years for all classes of vehicles was appropriate to fulfil the objectives of punishment, the protection of the public and deterrence. Although the Prosecution had sought a disqualification for a period of three years, I was of the view that the four years disqualification proposed by the Defence was more appropriate in the circumstances.

### Global Sentence

82     As the facts underlying the first charge under s 67 are in relation to the same act of driving which gave rise to second charge under s 65(1)(_a_), the offences engage an identical or largely overlapping set of facts. The operation of the enhanced penalty provision in s 65(5)(_c_) is contingent on the offender also being convicted of either an offence under ss 67 or 70(4) of the RTA.

83     Guided by the approach in _Wu Zhi Yong_, I ordered the sentences for both offences to run concurrently as the punishment for the offence of driving without due care and attention would already have been enhanced on account of the serious offender provision pursuant to s 65(5)(c) of the RTA. Hence, the global sentence was eight weeks’ imprisonment and disqualification from holding or obtaining all classes of driving licences for a period of five years with effect from the date of his release.
